segments.text: It is Wednesday, October 9th.
We are in the patio of Bob Cornish at 1214 Orris Street College Station.
And I am interviewing Joseph McGraw today, who will tell us about the early days of the planning department at Texas A&M University.
So, Joe, have at it.
My earliest recollection of starting anything related to planning, not necessarily department, but just thinking about it as a subject, was in a phone call made to me by Ed Romnick in 1958.
at Notre Dame, when I was teaching at Notre Dame.
And he asked if I would come down to Texas A&M and start teaching.
And in the course of that conversation, he mentioned that since Notre Dame didn't have a planning department then and I was only
teaching fourth-year architecture, that perhaps this would offer an opportunity to expand my teaching responsibilities to include planning.
And yet there was no planning program here, but we could begin to maybe work on that.
Ed was only then a fifth-year teacher.
I would teach the fourth year.
He would continue to teach the fifth year under a fellow by the name of Nicky Holliman.
Nicky Holliman was still dean.
He was head of the department.
It was called a division.
It was an architecture division.
I see.
And so I said, OK.
So Dean Benson, after some discussions with Dean Benson, formed an interdisciplinary committee.
And that was the title of it.
It was made up of people from civil engineering, sociology, the division of architecture,
several other people.
Do you remember any of the people?
Yeah, Jack Keys was one.
K-E-E-S?
K-E-E-S-E. Skrabanek from Sociology was another.
I was chairman of the committee.
I can probably find out who the other ones are, but those come to mind.
You had... Romnick was probably on it, too.
You had somebody from Parks and Recreation?
There was no Parks and Recreation Department then.
Uh-huh.
Now they have an entire building.
Right.
In fact, Parks and Recreation Department was started about a year or two after the Urban and Regional Planning Program started.
I even helped recruit faculty for that department.
Okay, well, then I came down here and in between 1958 and 1960,
This committee developed a proposal for planning, which I'll give you a copy of.
I've kept a copy of it.
It was formatted by the inimitable Ed Romnick in orange and red colors.
It's his favorite then and now.
This program in 1958, probably would have constituted, if adopted in 1958, would have been one of the first 30 schools of planning in the United States.
There were, I think, up to around 20 maybe schools in the United States.
It was presented to Earl Rutter and tabled by the Commission on Higher Education.
In Austin.
In Austin.
That very same proposal, and then I left for the coast and went to work for .
When it was stable, I figured,
It wasn't going to go very far, and they weren't quite ready for planning here.
In those days, I characterized the friends of the program called it socialism.
The enemies of the program or the proposal called it communism.
That was sort of the political climate in 1958, 59 in Texas.
So it wasn't, you know.
It hasn't changed much, has it?
I would not think so.
I mean, it's still regarded, I think, with some suspicion.
That needn't be typed.
No, that's right.
It's still regarded with some suspicion.
But anyhow, then that very same proposal was reactivated on the last legislative day of the Commission on Higher Education, which has now become the Coordinating Board for
of Texas.
And with the astuteness of which he was quite capable of, Earl Rudder got that program approved on the last day of the legislative life of the old Commission on Higher Education.
They didn't change one jot or tittle in the thing.
I wasn't even on board at school and all of those things that were in the proposal.
I then got another phone call from Ed Romnick.
It seems like it's making full circle.
Called me up at Wilsey Hammond Blair and asked me if I would come back and initiate and head up a program of urban planning at Texas A&M.
The proposal had been approved.
Do you remember what year that was?
Yeah, that was 1965.
And I said I would, you know.
And we negotiated my pay, my rank.
some promises about the program's autonomy later on, you know.
It currently started out as a division within the architecture school with Ed Romanek as dean and completely supported by Earl Ruddick.
And Holloman had retired by that time.
Yeah, Holloman had become the associate dean of the college.
No, he had not retired.
He had become the associate dean of the college specializing in student affairs and things like that.
He was an excellent man for keeping the records of the alumni and being an alumnus himself.
He was very good at that job.
Ed placed him well when he put him in that job.
Ed had returned from Columbia to become the dean.
Ed had returned from the West Coast to become the dean.
head of the planning program.
Wes Harper had come from Cordial, Rawlett & Scott to be head of the architecture department.
Alan Staso had become head of a brand new department called Environmental Design.
James Patterson headed up a research division.
And Jim Marsh was

the head of the department of building construction joe um you and uh wes and ed and maybe others for all i know uh knew each other before didn't you yeah this was a gathering of the clans yeah i was wes harper's roommate in college at oklahoma a m when we both went through architecture school and ed romnick was our fourth year professor in architecture he taught both the wes and
And he was a Harvard graduate.
He was instrumental, very instrumental in me going to Harvard and getting the master's degree in urban and regional planning.
In fact, it was at his suggestion that I even took the planning degree.
I didn't know whether he had lack of faith in me as an architecture student or whether he just saw this marvelous potential as an urban planner and suggested I go to Harvard and take that.
And he was very instrumental in me going there and getting a scholarship and all that kind of stuff.
where I met my mentor and major professor and then head of the Department of Urban Planning at Harvard, Reginald Isaacs.
When the proposal was renewed and reestablished and the program approved for Texas A&M, Reg Isaacs was one of the first guys I called to come down
He did this, by the way, at his own expense, because the planning program had no money, nothing.
He came down at his own expense, and as a personal favor to myself, to further the cause of planning in the Southwest.
And he came down, and they had a visit, and he met with all the faculty and the students of the college, and gave it.
a good explanation of what urban planning would do and his hopes for it and how he thought it would affect the other programs and things like that in a positive way.
And he solicited all their support.
And I thought he was very helpful in getting that initial support by doing that.
Probably needed someone with his reputation.
Right.
That was, let's see, what happened after that?
I'm trying to think what happened after that.
Oh, a new proposal was developed and put on board, and the... By the interdisciplinary committee?
No, that interdisciplinary committee wasn't reactivated with, you know... Oh, it was, it died.
It died, and...
Myself and Romanek and others began to develop the first curriculum in planning.
It was reviewed by Reg Isaacs.
He reviewed it and made subsequent contributions and things like that.
It was officially put on the books in about 19...
66, I think.
I'm not sure about that.
The next step was, of course, was to get it accredited.
We first started the steps towards accreditation at the St. Louis meeting of the AIP.
And that must have been in 1966 or 67.
I forget which.
I know Walter Ruther was the
keynote speaker of that thing, and it was there that I met Bob Williams and Israel Stolman.
I often thought, looking back on it, that it was at that meeting in that convention hotel that our
program was approved.
Because based on just the verbal outline of the program and the success we were having with acquiring students and things like that, they really indicated a lot of enthusiasm for the program.
Later on, Jim Gardner filled out and did the report on the actual documents for accreditation.
Jim Gardner, when did he come on board?
He came on board...
I came on the 65, 66 year.
He came on in the 67, 68 year.
Two years, I think.
One-five.
Two years.
I could be mistaken.
It could have been one year, but I have to look at it.
I want this thing double-spaced so I can, it'll jog my memory and I'll write some stuff in, okay?
Oh, yeah.
Okay.
And he prepared the report for accreditation, and it was accredited immediately after our first class graduated at the end of the two-year period, which is,
was a record time given that the University of Texas had on board a planning program that, to my knowledge, was about 20 years old under Hugo Leipzig or Pertus.
Hugo or the program were not widely supported by the administrative levels at the University of Texas like I was.
And I think therein lies the difference in the programs.
why ours was so rapidly accredited and Hugo's stayed in the doldrums for all those years, you see.
We had top-down support for this program and enjoyed a very quick accreditation, I think, as a result.
Our people at the National AIP and at ASPO knew we were serious about this.
And the A&M program was accredited before the UT program, even though they had been in business much longer.
Oh, yeah.

It seems like the competitive quality of our program got the administrators and people off the dime at the University of Texas, and they began to support both the program and Hugo with more enthusiasm than they had shown in the past.
Then the next person to be added to the planning faculty was Chuy Hinojosa, right?
Actually, I hired one of our first students, Mike Harney.
Mike Harney.
Right.
And he came on board.
And then Jesus Hinojosa.
And then Claude Davis, I think.
Not sure about this.
And then you.
I'm not sure whether you came before.
Was Claude here when you came?
Or after?
I got here in the fall of 1969, but taught in the architecture department for one year until a space was made on the faculty for me.
There was no position authorized at that time, as I understood it.
OK. Yeah, I guess that was it, wasn't it?
Yeah.
I remember I drove you free of charge back from San Francisco to College Station.
only to benefit by my superb company.
I know.
Wonderful.
That was it.

But that was also a gathering of the clans, too, because Jim Gardner, Jesus Hinojosa, myself, and Bob Cornish all worked together in an outfit called Will Z. Hammond Blair in the Bay Area of San Francisco.
And this constituted
the primary faculty and who were largely hired, they may not believe this, but they were largely hired for their strengths and divergent points of view on the planning process.
The only thing we held in common was that it should be at least comprehensive.
But we soon depart company after that.
And frankly, it was with the students in mind that diversity was brought on board.
We felt that in my architecture training, I never had enough diversity.
And I wasn't going to repeat that mistake in the planning program.
But now we've all come to know which point of view is correct.
It is correct.
Of course, mine.
That's how that started.
And I knew these divergent point of views, having worked with these gentlemen, and that was exactly why that was the main thrust in hiring.
In those days, there was no affirmative action or nothing.
You just went out and got the people that agreed to work with you.
And if they did, they were on board.
And the program enjoyed an awful lot of dynamics and flexibility in that regard in its beginning.

Another thing was that I don't think we saw the planning program here as one, another common thing we shared was that it must be comprehensive and it need not necessarily specialize in any given area of the planning process.
Those were options that an individual student could do, but that was not necessarily going to be the general thrust of the program.
It was not going to be transportation engineering or hospital planning or anything of the sort.
It was general planning in its broadest meaning and interdisciplinary in its nature.
And I guess also implicitly and explicitly by some of the faculty, we really thought
we would have more influence than history proved that we had on the rest of the programs.
We summed up one of the early graduates, Larry Priesmeier, who was a recent graduate in the architecture program and was recruited into the planning program.
And in one conference in the recruitment process where he was hesitant to join, he said, well, will I have to give up architecture when I get my master's degree in planning?

And what I said to him then, and I still believe in now, and I wish we were more effective in this, was I said, no, Larry, you'll just practice architecture differently as a result of having a plan to do it.
And I had high hopes that our program would do that.
It would influence the programs in engineering and architecture and landscape architecture to cope with the broader
social, political, and economic factors that work in their work and make them more aware of the implications toward design.
I'm not so sure a program was all that successful in that regard.
It was a goal that was never really attained in my book.

The planning faculty has attempted to work with the environmental design department, as you're painfully aware, particularly with the undergraduate programs, but also with other departments for graduate courses.

in achieving this and it's been an uphill struggle for various reasons i think most of which have to do with the politics of the college yeah and i also laid at the doorstep of having graduated from harvard who ostensibly was in the same boat of interdisciplinary sharing and working with one another a la gropius methods and techniques
It wasn't a practice anymore there, frankly, at the wellspring of all this thing that has been at Texas A&M.
And I really think that the behavior that we expect out of our students in this interdisciplinary activity isn't modeled by the faculty.
The faculty won't act interdisciplinary.
So how can we expect students to see the benefit of that if the faculties won't even do it?
Unilateral efforts have been made.
Jose and I worked together for Henry Cisneros, the mayor of San Antonio, one of our graduates in planning, you see.
Now on the Board of Regents.
Now on the Board of Regents of Texas A&M.
He and I, having separate classes, his in planning and mine in fourth-year design and environmental design, unilaterally worked out a common block of time where our students could work together.
When that contract was renewed for the second semester, administrative blocks were thrown in the way of us duplicating that effort.
When did that happen?
Well, that happened last year.
Yeah.
And so there doesn't seem to be a predisposition to interdisciplinary...
But that wasn't done by the planning department.
Oh, no, no, no.
The planning department was not at fault here.
It was my own department head who is no longer a department head.
He could not see his way clear to schedule my hours in such a way that they would match Chewy's.
And so...
Our students didn't participate in that rather successful project that Chewy did for the San Antonio area.
But this is the thing.
See, this is the thing.
It's always kind of held back.
The often used excuse that somehow the monies can't be allocated administratively to professors having joint appointments and that sort of thing is also just, I think, shibboleths and nonsense.
There isn't the commitment to our rhetoric here.
Makes a nice story, but really, the commitment's lacking.
The will to work interdisciplinary isn't here, either, among a good many of the faculty.
They want to do their own thing.
Of course, if this continues for any length of time, it leads to a general malaise.
Yeah, well, it'll lead to the individual
there will be other programs throughout the United States that really take advantage of the strength that's to be gained from interdisciplinary behavior and interdisciplinary work.
And we'll wonder why our programs are not as attractive as they used to be.
Well, for example, there are joint degree programs that have blossomed in a few of the more heads-up institutions.
You mentioned Harvard, and Harvard has a joint degree program with law
and planning, and so does Berkeley.
Right, right.
And I went to a joint program.
I did.
I took all my economics at MIT.
And they had a working relationship with a school down the road a piece.
And you took whatever courses you wanted over at MIT.
And then they, in turn, granted you the degree from one of the two schools, whichever you were resident in.
Yeah, so I was used to the interdisciplinary thing.
I was used to the thing.
I come to it very naturally, and I thought it was natural for people to do this.
The complexity of today's world almost demands that you have these kinds of approaches.
But not yet, and not here.
Yeah, I think...
You know, in those time-honored questions they ask you when you're on your 100th birthday, would you do it all differently?
And my answer to that is, no, I wouldn't do it any differently.
All I wanted to ever do, you know, and what I did was make a difference.
You know, the old time-honored Greek notion about that
Athens was better for you having lived there.
And I feel that with regard to our faculty and this program, that the state of Texas in planning and this university has been a little bit better for us having had this program here.
And I have absolutely no regrets, implied or otherwise, about the serious and meaningful contributions this program has made as it's evolved over the years.
And none of its graduates should, in my estimation, have any regrets regarding what they got here and what they've since done since they've left here.
It has produced some stellar people doing very effective jobs.
And we can all be proud of that.
